{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631876"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17406"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17406"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10096"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70503"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10096"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55967"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5347"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23661"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70503"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA factory worker is exposed to continuous noise during their shift. The following noise measurements were recorded:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAssembly line: 88 decibels\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBreak room: 75 decibels\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe safe reference level is 85 decibels for 8 hours of exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the most appropriate primary control measure for this noise exposure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provide ear plugs to workers","Install sound-absorbing barriers","Reduce shift length to 4 hours","Conduct annual hearing tests","Rotate workers every 2 hours"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate primary control measure is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einstall sound-absorbing barriers\u003C/strong\u003E. This follows the hierarchy of controls where engineering solutions are preferred over administrative controls or personal protective equipment (PPE).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide ear plugs to workers\u003C/strong\u003E represents a PPE solution which, whilst important, should not be relied upon as the primary control measure as it depends on worker compliance and correct usage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduce shift length to 4 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is an administrative control that reduces productivity and does not address the source of the hazard.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConduct annual hearing tests\u003C/strong\u003E is a form of health surveillance that detects damage after it occurs rather than preventing it.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotate workers every 2 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is an administrative control that does not eliminate the hazard and may expose more workers to noise risk.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEngineering controls like sound barriers address the hazard at its source and provide consistent protection without relying on worker compliance. This aligns with occupational health and safety principles of hazard elimination or minimisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Noise levels above 85 decibels for prolonged periods can cause permanent hearing damage.","Every 3 decibel increase doubles the sound intensity and halves the safe exposure time.","Engineering controls and personal protective equipment are essential for noise exposure management."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55967"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17406"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55967"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T18:54:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T18:55:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10096"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70503"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5326"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"posi